Good -- `oauth_account` IS defined in the schema (`option<record<connected_account>>`), so writes will persist. The schema is not the issue.

Now let me re-examine the callback flow more carefully to understand WHY `oauth_account` might not be set even after a successful OAuth flow. The key section is the callback handler's conditional nesting.

Looking at `server-routes.ts:911-941`:

```typescript
const encryptionKey = deps.config.toolEncryptionKey;
if (encryptionKey) {                                    // Gate 1
  const ownerIdentity = await findWorkspaceOwnerIdentity(...);
  if (ownerIdentity) {                                  // Gate 2
    // ... create connected_account ...
    await updateMcpServerOAuthAccount(deps.surreal, server.id, account.id);
  }
  // NO else branch -- silent failure if ownerIdentity is undefined
}
// NO else branch -- silent failure if encryptionKey is falsy
```

Then at line 944-948:
```typescript
await clearPendingOAuthState(deps.surreal, server.id);
await updateMcpServerStatus(deps.surreal, server.id, "ok");
triggerAutoSync(server as unknown as McpServerRecord);
```

These execute regardless of whether the account was created. The user sees `?oauth=success` redirect.

But both gates would typically pass in a functioning environment. Let me look at the `triggerAutoSync` call more closely. At line 948, `server` is the object from `findServerByPendingState` (line 857) -- this was fetched BEFORE t
...[truncated]
